Part II - Ford Gobike Data Exploration¶

by Teniola Alade¶

Investigation Overview¶

The investigation mainly involved how the effect of the age, the gender, the user-type of each user with respect to the days of the week played a role in how long the duration of trip was.

Dataset Overview¶

The dataset consists of information about 174,952 bike rides covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The data features include duration (secs), age, user type, gender etc.

Note that the above cells have been set as "Skip"-type slides. That means that when the notebook is rendered as http slides, those cells won't show up.

Univariate Analysis¶

Daily Bike Usage¶

More users rode the bike on Thursdays and Tuesdays, with a significant decrease on the weekends.

Distribution by Gender¶

Most users were Men - above 120000 Men, while about one-third were Women and the users in the other category recorded the lowest number.

Bivariate Analysis¶

Daily Ride Durations¶

Users rode the bike for a longer duration on the weekends than weekdays.

Ride Duration against User-type¶

Customers rode the bike longer than the subscribers.

Duration against Age¶

The olde rthe user, the shorter the trip duration and vice versa.

Gender against Duration¶

Male users had the shortest average trip duration of the three gender categories, with the Female and Other being marginally close

Multivariate Analysis¶

Daily Trip Duration by Gender¶

Other gender spent the most time on the bike. With the male gender spending the least time on the bike regardless of the day of the week. It also shows that all genders spent more time on the weekends than weekdays on the bike and the most time spent of the weekdays by the other gender was Thursday, followed by Monday.

Daily Trip Duration by User-Type¶

Customers spent a longer time riding the bike than the subscribers regardless of the day of the weeks, with both parties spending significantly more time on the weekends than weekdays. It can also be observed than customers spend more time on Monday than they did for any other weekday.

Key Insights¶

For the presentation, I focused on just the influence of the duration of the trip. I started by introducing the age variable, followed by the both the gender and user-type variables, and lastly the days of the week variable.

Afterwards, I introduced each of the categorical variables one by one. To start, I use the scatter plots of duration and age across gender . I'm only looking at the gender plot here to further understand how the gender affects the duration against age plot. Then, I also used a scatter plot of duration and age across user-type for further investigation into the bivariate plot.

The other categorical variables, days of the week, are covered afterwards, using point plots. I've made sure to use different color palettes for each quality variable to make sure it is clear that they're different between plots.
